EasyJet, HSBC Holdings, RBS, Shell: U.K., Irish Equity Preview

-- B y   B l a n c h e   G a t t
-- 
2011-07-13T06:49:56Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-12/easyjet-hsbc-holdings-rbs-shell-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
that may have unusual share-price changes in U.K. and Irish
markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses and prices are from
the last market close.  The FTSE 100 Index fell 60.20 points, or 1 percent, to
5,868.96. The FTSE All-Share Index dropped 1 percent to
3,057.70, while Ireland’s ISEQ Index retreated 0.5 percent to
2,887.14.  Burberry Group Plc (BRBY)  : The luxury-goods company
reported first-quarter sales of 367 million pounds ($585
million), beating the 344 million-pound average estimate of 11
analysts compiled by the company. The shares rose 1.6 percent to
1437 pence.  British Sky Broadcasting Plc (BSY LN): Prime Minister  David
Cameron ’s coalition government will today support an opposition
 Labour Party  motion calling for  News Corp . to withdraw its bid
to take full control of BSkyB. Barclays Plc and Sanford C.
Bernstein & Co. upgraded the shares. The stock dropped 3.3
percent to 692 pence.  EasyJet Plc (EZJ)  : EasyGroup Holdings Ltd. asked EasyJet
not to make any payments for its latest Airbus order
as announced on Jan. 4 until shareholder consent has been
secured. The stock slumped 3 percent to 323.6 pence.  HSBC Holdings Plc (HSBA)  :  Europe ’s biggest bank’s Turkey
unit had its standalone bank financial strength rating cut to D+
from C- by Moody’s Investors Service, which cited a combination
of “poor asset quality,” continuing contraction of loans
market share and “moderate profitability and efficiency
ratios.” HSBC shares fell 1.5 percent to 606.2 pence.  Marks and Spencer Group Plc (MKS LN): The food and clothing
retailer said comparable sales rose 1.7 percent, less that the 2
percent predicted by analysts, in the 13 weeks ended July 2. It
said it expects trading conditions to remain challenging. The
shares advanced 1.2 percent to 373 pence.  Royal Bank of Scotland Plc (RBS LN): The U.K.’s biggest
government-owned lender has proposed that parts of its riskier
investment banking units should be included in a planned ring-
fenced “safe” bank in a letter to a U.K. government
commission, the  Daily Telegraph  reported, without saying where
it obtained the information.  Separately, Better Capital Ltd. said that a company wholly
owned by BECAP Fund LP reached a formal agreement with RBS to
acquire a majority stake in Masco 30 Ltd., a new company set up
for the purpose of acquiring 100 percent of the share capital of
Fairline Boat Acquisitions Ltd. and its subsidiaries. The shares
gained 0.8 percent to 35.99 pence.  Royal Dutch Shell Plc (RDSA)  : Europe’s largest oil
company expects to receive by mid-October all U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency air permits it needs to start drilling off
Alaska’s coast next year, company Vice President Pete Slaiby
said. The stock retreated 1.6 percent to 2,209 pence.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Blanche Gatt in London at 
 bgatt@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
